Scottish independent schools maintain a curriculum of academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another series of outstanding results to the examinations, strengthened by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other collective efforts.
With over 30,000 pupils throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare pupils for further higher education, career choice and their place in the world as global citizens.
As an education sector able to develop and adopt a personalised school curriculum, we note that modern languages continue to be a popular subject and demand within schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to a man in a language that understands, the message will reach his brain.
If you speak to him in his mother tongue, the message will reach his heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone if we want to create trust relations with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's exams, we can see that the languages are at the top of the graduations, with the highest percentages of success within the independent schools.
68% of the students who studied foreign languages got the highest vote.
The data collected by the 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72% of students obtained the highest vote with Chinese praise, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish received the highest vote.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as fundamental skills for children and young people, who will undoubtedly need them in the future.
Languages, as a matter choice, are currently considered at the same level as STEM materials (science, technology, technology and mathematics) in the study plans of independent institutions and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the United Kingdom Commission on Employment and Skills in 2014 found that the reasons why employees have shown the difficulty in covering jobs are attributable in 17% of cases to a lack of language skills.
This is why language skills are becoming increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more job opportunities requiring language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career chosen, if you have learned a second language, you will have an effective advantage in the future with a life skills like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically lead a multilingual person to competition.
According to a survey by YouGov of over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language at a sufficient level to maintain a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%.
That is why investing in language teaching is so important for children today.
Knowledge of more languages, especially those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a valid job.
In Scotland, every school will differ in the languages taught.
Several schools will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the United Kingdom by looking at 2020, such as Chinese Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with the specialized teaching staff in this field.
Independent schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the necessary skills for success, regardless of their future.
It is not possible to deny at this time, in a global trading system, that languages continue to be fundamental to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in teaching.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communicative competences."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence for young people in Scotland.
We have to do this.
