"Without trust in the USA there will be no security in our national security and in such circumstances we absolutely refuse to disarm ourselves unilaterally first."
Although Ri has re-used the complaints concerning Washington's resistance to a "in stages" denuclearisation with which North Korea would be awarded on the basis of gradual actions, his statement has been important because it has not completely refused unilateral denuclearisation as it has already done in the past by Pyongyang.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first absolute meeting between a US President in office and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on 12 June, when Kim committed to working towards "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula", while Trump promised guarantees for North Korean security.
North Korea sought a formal end-of-war agreement in the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States stated that Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington also opposed appeals to slow down the rigid international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
"The USA insists on the need to "have denuclearization first" and to increase the level of pressure with sanctions in order to achieve their purpose in a coercive way and even oppose the "declaration of the end of war," Ri said.
"The idea that sanctions can put us on our knees is an illusion of those who don't know anything about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions is increasing our distrust."
Ri did not refer to programmes for a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the US leader had announced to the UN at the beginning of the week.
On the other hand, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If the counterpart of this issue of denuclearization was South Korea and not the USA, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be at this point dead."
But even so, the tone of Ri's speech was significantly different from last year's speech at the UN General Assembly, when he stated that it was inevitable to target the US territory with the North Korean missiles after "the President of Evil" Trump had called Kim a "missile man" engaged in a suicide mission.
In front of the United Nations Trump, who threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea last year, he praised Kim for her courage in embarking on the disarmament path, but stated that much still needs to be done and that sanctions will remain in place until North Korea's denuclearisation.
Wednesday Trump said he didn't have a deadline, stating that "if it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
