HIV/AIDS: China reports an increase of 14% of new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of citizens affected by HIV and AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected by these diseases, according to sources of health authorities.
Some 40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of new cases are due to sexual transmission, which marks a change from the past.
In some regions of China HIV has spread in the past as a result of transfusions of infected blood.
But the number of people who have contracted HIV in this way has fallen to almost zero, according to the Chinese health authorities at a conference in Yunnan province.
Year after year, however, the number of people affected by HIV and AIDS in China increased by 100,000 units.
The transmission of HIV by sex is an urgent problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is still widespread.
Because of the traditional values of the country, some studies have estimated that 70-90% of men who have sex with other men eventually marry women.
Many of the transmissions of diseases are caused by inadequate protections during sexual relations within these relationships.
In 2003, the Chinese government promised universal access to anti-HIV drugs as part of its commitment to managing the problem.
