The new German military ship was postponed again
According to local media, the last fray of the German military Navy would have to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the old military ships of the times of the cold war, but there will not be until next year at least due to defective systems and a high cost.
The commission of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the Admiral ship of the new frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class, was postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit that mentions a military spokesperson.
The ship was supposed to join the military Navy in 2014, but worrying subsequent delivery issues tormented the fate of the ambitious project.
The four ships of the Baden-Württemberg class ordered by the military Navy in 2007 will replace the old vessels of the Bremen class.
They will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some hidden technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic markings.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods, in fact it should be possible to use new cargoes up to two years away from national ports.
However, the continued delays imply that the innovative warships, which are said to allow Germany to project its overseas power, will become obsolete when they enter into service, notes Die Zeit.
The unfortunate fray Type F-125 made news last year, when the German military Navy officially refused to commission the ship and returned it to the ship yard Blohm & Voss in Hamburg.
It was the first time the military Navy returned a ship to the manufacturer after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but the German media noticed a number of crucial "software and hardware" that made the ship useless if employed in a combat mission.
The deficiencies in the software were particularly important as the Baden-Württemberg class ships will be managed by a crew of about 120 sailors, just half of the staff of the oldest vessels in the Bremen class.
Moreover, it emerged that the ship weighs heavily too much, and this reduces its performance and limits the possibility of the military Navy to add future updates.
Rheinland-Pfalz, 7,000 tons, is thought to be twice as heavy as similar class ships used by the Germans in World War II.
Apart from faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project (including crew training) is becoming an important issue.
It seems that it has reached EUR 3.1 billion (USD 3.6 billion) from the initial €2.2 billion.
The problems involving the new sinks become of particular importance in the light of recent alarms concerning the reduction of German naval power.
At the beginning of the year, Hans-Peter Bartels, parliamentary commissioner for the Armed Forces, admitted that the military Navy actually "discharges ships able to be employed".
The official stated that the issue has worsened considerably over time, since the old unarmed ships have not been replaced by new ships.
