The National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
New research carried out in a Scottish Highland estate aims to reveal how bats use the view to get their food.
It is hoped that the discoveries can shed light on the behaviour of the only existing flying mammals and guide future protective activities.
The study of the scientists of the National Trust for Scotland will follow common and soprano bats, as well as the brown ears and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens, in Western Ross.
Special registrants will be placed in key places around the property to track the activities of bats during the season.
The NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using portable detectors.
The analysis of the recorded sounds by an expert will determine the frequency of the bat calls and the manner in which each species behaves.
A habitat map and a report will then be produced to create a detailed picture on the scale of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, an advisor for nature protection for the NTS, hopes that the results can reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of meadows, and how to better maintain forests for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined considerably in the last century.
